04283nam a22006615i 9781442685062DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192007onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426850627 a10.3138/97814426850622doi  a(DE-B1597)497084  a(OCoLC)1083578923  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a307.1/416097135412221 aSolomon, Lawrence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aToronto Sprawls :bA History /cLawrence Solomon. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (128 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aU of T Centre for Public Management Series on Public Policy & Administration00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Toronto circa 1900, before the Era of Sprawl -- t1. How Private Transit Hobbled Sprawl -- t2. Living at Close Quarters -- t3. Toronto the Good -- t4. Model People, Model Suburbs -- t5. Canada’s War Effort against the Cities -- t6. CMHC and Cheap Financing Open Up the Suburbs -- t7. Partial Amalgamation, Full Sprawl -- t8. The Suburbs beyond the Suburbs -- tConclusion: How Toronto Might Have Been -- tPostscript: Toronto in 2020 -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith a landmass of approximately 7000 square kilometres and a population of roughly five million, the Greater Toronto Area is Canada's largest metropolitan centre. How did a small nineteenth-century colonial capital become this sprawling urban giant, and how did government policies shape the contours of its landscape?In Toronto Sprawls, Lawrence Solomon examines the great migration from farms to the city that occurred in the last half of the nineteenth century. During this period, a disproportionate number of single women came to Toronto while, at the same time, immigration from abroad was swelling the city's urban boundaries. Labour unions were increasingly successful in recruiting urban workers in these years. Governments responded to these perceived threats with a series of policies designed to foster order. To promote single family dwellings conducive to the traditional family, buildings in high-density areas were razed and apartment buildings banned. To discourage returning First World War veterans from settling in cities, the government offered grants to spur rural settlement. These policies and others dispersed the city's population and promoted sprawl.An illuminating read, Toronto Sprawls makes a convincing case that urban sprawl in Toronto was caused not by market forces, but rather by policies and programs designed to disperse Toronto's urban population.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCities and townszOntariozTorontoxGrowthxHistory. 0aCity planningzOntariozTorontoxHistory. 0aUrban policyzOntariozTorontoxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aDhar, Satish, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268506240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442685062423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442685062.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK